===Etymology 2===
Possibly from {{m|en|aye}}.

The pirate-imitation form was derived from the [[w:West Country English|West Country dialect]] after its use by [[West Country]]-born actor {{w|Robert Newton}} (1905–1956) in the films ''[[w:Treasure Island (1950 film)|Treasure Island]]'' (1950) and ''{{w|Blackbeard the Pirate}}'' (1952)—and the former’s spin-off media—in which he played, respectively, the fictional pirate {{w|Long John Silver}} and the historical pirate [[w:Blackbeard|Edward “Blackbeard” Teach]] (c. 1680 – 1718; also a West Country native).<ref>{{cite-book|author=Peter Grego|chapter=‘Aharrr, Jim Lad!’|title=Cornwall's Strangest Tales: Extraordinary but True Stories|series=Strangest Series|location=London|publisher=[[w:Pavilion Books|Portico]]|year=2013|isbn=978-1-909396-00-5}}.</ref><ref>{{cite-book|author=Amy M. Davis|title=Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films|location=Bloomington, Ind.|publisher={{w|Indiana University Press}}|year=2014|isbn=978-0-86196-704-9|page=193}}.</ref><ref>{{cite-book|author=Gary Holpin|title=Exmouth to Plymouth: Britain's Heritage Coast|series=Britain's Heritage Coast|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|year=2014|isbn=978-1-4456-2157-9}}.</ref>

